      "content": "The escrow agent doesn't actually make the final decision on the dispute itself; that is a crucial distinction to make, as the agent is more like a neutral scribe than a judge. Their primary role is to follow the specific instructions written in the Purchase Agreement and the inspection addendum.\n\nIf the inspection reveals issues and the seller refuses to fix them, the process usually hinges on the \"repair request\" clause in your contract. You and the seller negotiate a resolution—either the seller agrees to make repairs, you agree to waive those specific issues, or you decide to walk away entirely. Once that negotiation is settled and agreed upon by both parties, you sign a formal addendum or amendment.\n\nOnly after that addendum is signed and delivered to the escrow agent does the agent proceed to release funds or close the deal. If the seller refuses to sign the necessary addendum, the buyer typically has the right to terminate the contract based on the inspection contingency, and the escrow agent will simply release the funds back to the buyer. The agent acts as the gatekeeper ensuring the paperwork is legally compliant, but the actual \"say\" belongs to the negotiated agreement between the buyer and seller.\n\nIt's worth noting that in some rare cases",
